\begin_layout Standard
So how much should you pay for such a right (either call or put)? Alternatively
 how much can you charge if you're selling such a contract? The basic idea
 in figuring out how to price such a contract is to assume that no arbitrages
 exist in the market and use delta hedging (fractional shares) to construct
 a perfect hedge (one that eliminates all risk from a portfolio).
 Since the portfolio is riskless it must earn interest at the risk-free
 rate.
 From this you can calculate the value of the portfolio at expiration and
 work backwards to see how much the option should have the buyer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Black-Scholes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Black-Scholes model was constructed by Fischer Black and Myron Scholes
 in 1973, based on work by Robert Merton.
 Merton and Scholes won the Nobel in Economics in 97 (Black was ineligible
 having died in 95).
 It forms the basis for much more complicated investment strategies used
 by hedge funds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The BlackScholes model assumes that the market consists of at least one
 risky asset, usually called the stock, and one riskless asset, usually
 called the money market, cash, or bond.
 The assumptions on market are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is no arbitrage opportunity (i.e., there is no way to make a riskless
 profit).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is possible to borrow and lend any amount, even fractional, of cash at
 the riskless rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is possible to buy and sell any amount, even fractional, of the stock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The above transactions do not incur any fees or costs (i.e., frictionless
 market).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumptions on the assets are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The rate of return on the riskless asset is constant and thus called the
 risk-free interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The instantaneous log returns of the stock price is a geometric Brownian
 motion, and we will assume its drift and volatility is constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The stock does not pay a dividend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Per the model assumptions above, the price of the underlying asset (typically
 a stock) follows a geometric Brownian motion.
 That is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dS}{S}=\mu dt+\sigma dB
\]

\end_inset

We now construct a portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 consisting of some number of European call options on the stock and some
 number of shares which is a perfect hedge (riskless).
 First the price of the call option 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a stochastic process and clearly a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 So by Ito's lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dV=\left(\mu S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)dt+\sigma S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}dB
\]

\end_inset

Now delta-hedging portfolio that turns out to be a perfect hedge is to sell
 1 option and buy 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}$
\end_inset

 shares of the stock.
 It will become clear in a moment why this is the portfolio that turns out
 to be a perfect hedge.
 The value of this portfolio/holdings is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi=-1\times V+\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}S
\]

\end_inset

Why? First note that we're on the sell side of the option.
 Meaning we have sold someone else the right to sell us something, at the
 expiration of the option.
 What happens if the price of the stock exceeds the strike price of the
 option? Then it wouldn't make sense for the buyer to sell us shares of
 the stock at the strike price because they would be losing money.
 Alternatively if the price of the stock is below the strike price then
 it does make sense for the buyer to sell us shares of the underlying.
 This is the value 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of the option and to us it's a loss (because end up paying above market
 rate for the shares).
 Because we're on the sell side of the option (we sold a call option).
 On the otherhand the value of our holdings in the underlying 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}S\right)$
\end_inset

 is a gain (since the shares simply have their face value).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Discretizing the differentials in
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

: from 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\Delta t$
\end_inset

 the net change in the value of the portfolio is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\Pi=-\Delta V+\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}\Delta S
\]

\end_inset

Similarly discretising the process that defines 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Delta S & = & \mu S\Delta t+\sigma S\Delta B\\
\Delta V & = & \left(\mu S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}+\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)\Delta t+\sigma S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}\Delta B
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Note ratios of differentials haven't been discretised because _______.
 Now substituting into 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Pi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\Pi=\left(-\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)\Delta t
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta B$
\end_inset

 dependence drops out.
 The portfolio is now riskless (independent of the stochastic volatility
 in the market).
 Therefore the rate of return must be the risk-free rate 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (otherwise there would be arbitrage in the market because you could earn
 money on this riskless portfolio at a greater rate than the risk-free rate).
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta\Pi=r\Pi\Delta t
\]

\end_inset

If this is unrecognizable think 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\Pi}{dt}=r\Pi
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 continuously compounding interest.
 Equating the two expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\Pi$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}\right)\Delta t=r\left(-V+S\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}\right)\Delta t
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+rS\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0
\]

\end_inset

the Black-Scholes equation.
 Solving this PDE with boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}V(0,t) & =0\text{ for all }t\\
V(S,t) & \rightarrow S\text{ as }S\rightarrow\infty\\
V(S,T) & =\max\left\{ S-K,0\right\} 
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset

gives the value of the option for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\leq T$
\end_inset

.
 To actually solve recognize it as a Cauchy-Euler equation which can be
 transformed into a diffusion equation with the change of variables
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tau & = & T-t\\
u & = & Ve^{r\tau}\\
x & = & \ln\left(\frac{S}{K}\right)+\left(r-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\right)\tau
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

to produce
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial\tau}=\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

with boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(S,T\right)=\max\left\{ S-K,0\right\} $
\end_inset

 becoming initial condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(x,0\right)=u_{0}\left(x\right)=K\left(e^{\max\left\{ x,0\right\} }-1\right)
\]

\end_inset

The standard solution is by method of Green's functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
u\left(x,\tau\right) & = & \frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi\tau}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}u_{0}\left(y\right)e^{-\frac{\left(x-y\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}\tau}}dy\\
 & = & Ke^{x+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\tau}\Phi\left(d_{1}\right)-K\mathcal{\Phi}\left(d_{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is the CDF of a standard normal and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}d_{1} & =\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{\tau}}\left[\left(x+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\tau\right)+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\tau\right]\\
d_{2} & =\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{\tau}}\left[\left(x+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\tau\right)-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}\tau\right]
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset


